\begin_layout Standard
A thin lens corresponds to a lens for which the distance between its front
 and back interfaces can be neglected without introducing significant errors
 in the description of ray propagation.
 As shown in Figure 1 for the case of a plano-convex lens, a simple system
 made up of an object in front of a thin lens can be described by the parameters
 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{o}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, which correspond to the object distance, the image distance, and the lens's
 focal length, respectively.
 These three quantities are related by the thin lens equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{1}{s_{o}}+\frac{1}{s_{i}}=\frac{1}{f}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The transverse magnification 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{T}$
\end_inset

, defined as the ratio of the image height 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}$
\end_inset

 to that of the object height 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
M_{T}=\frac{y_{i}}{y_{o}}=-\frac{s_{i}}{s_{o}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A negative magnification implies that the image is inverted, whereas a positive
 magnification corresponds to an erect image.
 All real images formed by an optical system composed by a single thin lens
 will be inverted, because the quantities 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{o}$
\end_inset

 are always positive for real objects and images.
 As shown in the figure, we can calculate the magnification and the image
 distance of an object if we know the object's distance from the lens and
 the lens's focal length by drawing a ray parallel to the axis that emerges
 from the top of the object, passes through the lens and then crosses the
 focal point to the right of the lens, and another ray that emerges from
 the same point and then passes through the center of the lens without being
 deviated.
 The point at which these two rays intersect corresponds to the position
 of the top of the image.
 This sort of ray tracing technique can be very useful when applied to more
 complicated systems involving more than one lens.
 Convex lenses have a positive focal length, whereas concave lenses have
 a negative focal length.
 This implies that concave lenses are divergent, and convex lenses are convergen
t.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Systems consisting of more than one lens can be used as beam expanders,
 because they have a magnification greater than 1.
 Two types of beam expanders are the Galilean beam expander and the Keplerian
 beam expander.
 The Galilean beam expander consists of a diverging lens of focal length
 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}$
\end_inset

 and a converging lens of focal length 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}$
\end_inset

 separated by a distance 
\begin_inset Formula $d=f_{1}+f_{2}$
\end_inset

, as shown in Figure 2.
 The magnification of such a system is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
M_{G}=\frac{-f_{2}}{f_{1}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Keplerian beam expander, on the other hand, consists of two convex lenses,
 separated by a distance of 
\begin_inset Formula $d=f_{1}+f_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 This is shown in Figure 3.
 Note that this distance will be in general greater than that of the Galilean
 expander because now both focal lengths are positive.
 The magnification of this system is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
M_{K}=\frac{f_{2}}{f_{1}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will attempt to build both types of expanders in the last part of this
 project.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Ray transfer matrices and the paraxial approximation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A very useful way to describe the propagation of a ray is via the use of
 ray transfer matrices.
 In the context of laser optics, this approach can also be made simpler
 by working under the so-called paraxial approximation.
 If the object and image distances are large with respect to the transverse
 size of the lenses used in the optical system, the angle at which a ray
 can emerge from an object has to be small in order for the ray to pass
 through the lens as it propagates.
 This allows us to use the small-angle approximation, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin\theta\approx\tan\theta\approx\theta$
\end_inset

, and implies that we can assume that the rays are very close to parallel
 to the optical axis: they are paraxial.
 Under this framework, we can relate the height 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and the angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 of a ray with respect to the optical axis via the equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left[\begin{array}{c}
y\\
\theta
\end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
A & B\\
C & D
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{c}
y_{0}\\
\theta_{0}
\end{array}\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the matrix is known as the ray transfer or ABCD matrix, and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{0}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

 correspond to the initial height and angle of the ray.
 The components of the matrix depend on the specific structures through
 which the ray travels.
 For the purposes of this project, it is enough to introduce the ABCD matrices
 for a ray travelling a distance 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 through free space, and a ray crossing a thin lens of focal length 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 These are given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
M_{FS} & = & \left[\begin{array}{cc}
1 & d\\
0 & 1
\end{array}\right]\\
M_{TL} & = & \left[\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
\nicefrac{-1}{f} & 1
\end{array}\right]
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The transfer matrix of a ray travelling through a combination of structures
 can be found by multiplying the matrices of each of these structures.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Gaussian waves
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
General definitions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The amplitude of the electric field of the light emitted by a laser can
 be successfully described by a Gaussian distribution.
 Following the descriptions given in [3] and [4], we can write the absolute
 value of the normalized electric field amplitude of a laser beam propagating
 in the z-direction as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left|\frac{E(x,\,y,\,z)}{E_{0}}\right|=\frac{w_{0}}{w(z)}\exp\left(-\frac{r^{2}}{w^{2}}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the beam waist, defined as the point in which the field
 is down by 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{-1}$
\end_inset

 with respect to the field's strength at 
\begin_inset Formula $r=0$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{0}=w(z_{0})$
\end_inset

, which corresponds to the minimum value of the beam waist.
 The intensity of the beam as a function of the distance from the beam center
 is proportional to the square of the electric field, and is thus given
 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
I=I_{0}\exp\left(\frac{-2r^{2}}{w^{2}}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{0}=\frac{w_{0}^{2}}{w(z)^{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 The evolution of the beam waist as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 is related to the minimum radius 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{0}$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
w(z)=w_{0}\sqrt{1+\left(\frac{z-z_{0}}{z_{R}}\right)^{2}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{R}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the Rayleigh range,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
z_{R}=\frac{\pi w_{0}^{2}}{\lambda}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 being the wavelength of the light.
 Equation (10) can be rewritten in terms of the beam diameter 
\begin_inset Formula $D=2w$
\end_inset

 and related to the far field divergence angle
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta$
\end_inset

 by the equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
D(z)=\sqrt{D_{0}^{2}+\left[\Theta(z-z_{0})\right]^{2}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Far away from the beam waist, when 
\begin_inset Formula $z-z_{0}\gg z_{R}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta$
\end_inset

 approaches 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{2w(z)}{z-z_{0}}$
\end_inset

, and it follows that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Theta=\frac{2\lambda}{\pi w_{0}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equation (13) will provide a useful check on our measurements.
 This equation is also a manifestation of Liouville's theorem in optics.
 This theorem asserts that the phase space volume of system is conserved,
 which in this context means that the product of the divergence and the
 beam waist is always equal to a constant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Calculating the beam size
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the beam size of a laser is very small, it is not possible to measure
 small variations in its size by measuring its diameter using a ruler.
 Instead, we do this by observing how the beam intensity changes as we block
 part of the beam.
 If the size of the spot is small compared to the collecting area of the
 photosensor, the total intensity can be approximated as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
I_{tot}=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}I_{0}e^{\nicefrac{-2r^{2}}{w^{2}}}dr
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Blocking half of the beam (in this context, using a razor blade) results
 in an intensity of 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{\nicefrac{1}{2}}=\frac{I_{tot}}{2}$
\end_inset

.
 If we now translate the razor blade a horizontal distance 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x$
\end_inset

 such that the recorded intensity becomes a quarter of the original intensity,
 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{\nicefrac{1}{4}}=\frac{I_{tot}}{4}=\frac{I_{\nicefrac{1}{2}}}{2}$
\end_inset

, we can find the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 by solving the following equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{I_{\nicefrac{1}{2}}}{I_{\nicefrac{1}{4}}} & = & \frac{\int_{0}^{\infty}I_{0}e^{\nicefrac{-2r^{2}}{w^{2}}}dr}{\int_{\Delta x}^{\infty}I_{0}e^{\nicefrac{-2r^{2}}{w^{2}}}dr}\\
 & = & \frac{\int_{0}^{\infty}e^{\nicefrac{-2r^{2}}{w^{2}}}dr}{\int_{0}^{\infty}e^{\nicefrac{-2r^{2}}{w^{2}}}dr-\int_{0}^{\Delta x}e^{\nicefrac{-2r^{2}}{w^{2}}}dr}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the LHS of this equation is equal to 2, we can write this as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{1}{2}=1-\frac{\int_{0}^{\Delta x}e^{\nicefrac{-2r^{2}}{w^{2}}}dr}{\int_{0}^{\infty}e^{\nicefrac{-2r^{2}}{w^{2}}}dr}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the solution of the Gaussian integral and solving for 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
w=\frac{\Delta x\sqrt{2}}{\erf\left(\nicefrac{1}{2}\right)}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can use (18) to calculate the spot size when we are not too far away
 from 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{0}$
\end_inset

, but measuring the beam's divergence 
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta$
\end_inset

 is better done far away from 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{0}$
\end_inset

, where the spot size becomes comparable to the size of the photosensor's
 collecting area.
 In that case, (18) ceases to be accurate.
 A better approximation can be performed by taking into account the photosensor'
s shape and size.
 For a square photosensor with side length 
\begin_inset Formula $2a$
\end_inset

, the measured intensity when half of the beam is blocked is (assuming the
 sensor is positioned right behind the razor blade)
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
I_{\nicefrac{1}{2}}=I_{0}\int_{0}^{a}e^{\nicefrac{-2x^{2}}{w^{2}}}dx\int_{0}^{2a}e^{\nicefrac{-2y^{2}}{w^{2}}}dy
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Translating the razor a horizontal distance 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x$
\end_inset

 such that the new intensity is half of 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{\nicefrac{1}{2}}$
\end_inset

, we see that this new intensity is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
I_{\nicefrac{1}{4}}=I_{0}\int_{\Delta x}^{a}e^{\nicefrac{-2x^{2}}{w^{2}}}dx\int_{0}^{2a}e^{-\nicefrac{-2y^{2}}{w^{2}}}dy
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Dividing this two expressions gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{I_{\nicefrac{1}{2}}}{I_{\nicefrac{1}{4}}}=\frac{\int_{0}^{a}e^{\nicefrac{-2x^{2}}{w^{2}}}dx}{\int_{\Delta x}^{a}e^{\nicefrac{-2x^{2}}{w^{2}}}dx}=2
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We use the solution to the Gaussian integral again to get
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\erf\left(\frac{a\sqrt{2}}{w}\right)-2\erf\left(\frac{\Delta x\sqrt{2}}{w}\right)=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This equation needs to be solved numerically for 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

, since it is not possible to solve it analytically.
 There is very little difference between the values for 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 obtained for a given 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x$
\end_inset

 using equation (18) and those obtained using (22) when 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x$
\end_inset

 is small compared to 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

, but the differences become noticeable once 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x$
\end_inset

 gets bigger, which occurs when we measure the beam diameter far away from
 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{0}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Shadowgraphy and Schlieren photography
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In some engineering applications, especially in fluid dynamics and aerospace
 engineering, it is very useful to observe the way fluids flow and how they
 are affected by the presence of an object and changes in their temperature.
 This can be done by setting up a system that allows one to indirectly observe
 changes in the refractive index of the fluid.
 The most basic of these systems is the shadowgraph, and a more advanced
 one is the Schlieren system.
 Both systems rely on the fact that that the refractive index of a fluid
 is related to its density in such a way that a fluid with non-uniform density
 also has a non-uniform refractive index.
 The shadowgraph is able to capture these density differences by shining
 light through the medium and looking at the shadow cast by it due to refraction.
 In such a system, the observed light intensity is proportional to the Laplacian
 of the fluid's density.
 On the other hand, the more sophisticated Schlieren system is similar to
 the shadowgraph but also utilizes a focusing element and a knife edge in
 order to take advantage of the fact that the non-uniformity of the fluid
 results in imperfect focusing, and the resulting light intensity is then
 proportional to the first derivative of the fluid's density.
 A more quantitative analysis of the shadowgraph and the Schlieren system
 can be found in [5].
 We will attempt to build a shadowgraph and a Schlieren system in the last
 part of this project.
\end_layout

