\begin_layout Standard
We now switch back to a configuration similar to the one used in experiment
 1B, with the difference that now the lens is placed on top of a translation
 stage and a rotation stage at the same time, as shown in Figure 8.
 This enables us to vary both the angle of the ray, as we did in experiment
 1B, and the height at which the ray emerges, as we did in 1C (i).
 The goal is to find the appropriate 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{o}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

 such that translating the mirror does not result in any motion of the spot,
 but rotating the mirror does.
 Note that in this context, 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the distance between the beam stopper and the lens.
 A ray diagram for the setup is shown in Figure 9.
 In terms of the quantities represented on this diagram, translating the
 mirror corresponds to a change in 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{0}$
\end_inset

, and rotating the mirror corresponds to a variation in 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 We can use the ray transfer matrix method within the paraxial approximation
 described in section 2.2 in order to find the necessary conditions that
 result in 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2}$
\end_inset

 being independent from 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{0}$
\end_inset

, but not independent from 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 We can relate 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{2}$
\end_inset

 via the matrix equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\left[\begin{array}{c}
y_{2}\\
\theta_{2}
\end{array}\right] & = & \left[\begin{array}{cc}
1 & s_{i}\\
0 & 1
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
\nicefrac{-1}{f} & 1
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{cc}
1 & s_{o}\\
0 & 1
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{c}
y_{0}\\
\theta_{0}
\end{array}\right]\\
 & = & \left[\begin{array}{c}
y_{0}+\theta_{0}(s_{o}+s_{i})-\frac{s_{i}(y_{0}+s_{o}\theta_{0})}{f}\\
\theta_{0}-\frac{y_{0}+s_{o}\theta_{0}}{f}
\end{array}\right]
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to find the 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{o}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

 that result in 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2}$
\end_inset

 being independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{0}$
\end_inset

, we take the derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2}$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{0}$
\end_inset

 and set it equal to zero:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{dy_{2}}{dy_{0}}=1-\frac{s_{i}}{f}=0
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Solving for 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

 gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s_{i}=f
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Taking the derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2}$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{0}$
\end_inset

 and using this result, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{dy_{2}}{d\theta_{0}}=s_{o}+s_{i}-\frac{s_{i}s_{o}}{f}=f
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These two results imply that the experimental goal can be achieved simply
 by placing the beam stopper at a distance 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 from the lens, independently of the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{o}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

