\begin_layout Standard
In this experiment, we measure the focal length 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}$
\end_inset

 of a plano-concave lens with nominal value of -2.5 cm.
 The setup is shown in Figure 12.
 We place an 0.5 ND filter inmediately in front of the laser, and a mirror
 some reasonable distance away from it.
 We now place the plano-concave lens with its concave side facing the mirror
 at a distance 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{o1}$
\end_inset

, in a position that makes a 
\begin_inset Formula $\thicksim90^{\circ}$
\end_inset

 angle with the original direction of propagation of the beam.
 Next, we mount a plano-convex lens of focal length 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{2}=10$
\end_inset

 cm in front of the concave lens at a distance 
\begin_inset Formula $d>10$
\end_inset

 cm.
 Finally, we place the beam stopper behind the convex lens, and find the
 image distance of the convex lens 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i2}$
\end_inset

using the same procedure as in experiment 1B: by looking for the position
 of the beam stopper that results in no motion of the beam spot when the
 mirror is rotated.
 Based on these measurements, we can calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}$
\end_inset

 as follows.
 Using the thin lens approximation, we have the following two equations
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{1}{f_{1}} & = & \frac{1}{s_{i1}}+\frac{1}{s_{o1}}\\
\frac{1}{f_{2}} & = & \frac{1}{s_{i2}}+\frac{1}{s_{o2}}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i1}$
\end_inset

 is related to 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{o2}$
\end_inset

 by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s_{i1}=d-s_{o2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Combining (32) with (30) and solving for 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}$
\end_inset

 gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f_{1}=\frac{s_{o1}(d-s_{o2})}{s_{o1}+d-s_{o2}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, solving for 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{o2}$
\end_inset

 in (31) and substituting
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f_{1}=\frac{s_{o1}d(s_{i2}-f_{2})-f_{2}s_{o1}s_{i2}}{(s_{i2}-f_{2})(s_{o1}+d)-f_{2}s_{i2}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Results and analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We used a distance between the convex and concave lens 
\begin_inset Formula $d=20.0\pm0.2$
\end_inset

 cm, and a distance between the mirror and the concave lens 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{o1}=22.8\pm0.2$
\end_inset

 cm.
 The measured image distance was 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i2}=18.0\pm0.5$
\end_inset

 cm, which gives a focal length 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}=-2.8\pm1.0$
\end_inset

 cm.
 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}$
\end_inset

 was taken as 
\begin_inset Formula $10\pm0.1$
\end_inset

 cm.
 The large value in the uncertainty of 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i2}$
\end_inset

 derives, as in previous experiments, from the qualitative aspect of the
 procedure used to determine it.
 Even though the individual uncertainties of the measured values are not
 large relative to their nominal value, propagation of the error results
 in a large uncertainty for the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}$
\end_inset

, due to the large number of operations that need to be performed between
 the quantities in order to arrive to the result.
 This also implies that relatively small changes in the measured value for
 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i2}$
\end_inset

 introduce large variations in the computed value of 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 For instance, using 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i2}=18.5\pm0.5$
\end_inset

 cm gives 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}=-1.9\pm0.8$
\end_inset

 cm, and using 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i2}=19\pm0.5$
\end_inset

 cm yields 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{1}=-1.2\pm0.7$
\end_inset

 cm.
 This suggests that this method of measuring the focal length is not very
 reliable, unless one is able to determine the distances with a large degree
 of precision.
\end_layout

